body:
### Version

Yosys 0.26+34 (git sha1 a20804c6e, clang 13.0.0 -fPIC -Os)

### On which OS did this happen?

macOS

### Reproduction Steps

The following verilog  sythesizes using BRAM on ice40:

```
   reg [31:0] ram[0:(mem_size*256)-1];
   reg [31:0] ram_read;

   wire [$clog2(mem_size*256):0] ram_read_addr;

   always @(posedge clk) begin
     if (prog_mode) begin
        ram_read_addr <= prog_addr >> 1;
     end else if (!rst_out) begin
        if (dBus_cmd_valid && !dBus_cmd_payload_wr && dbus_ram_access)
          ram_read_addr <= dBus_cmd_payload_address[15:2];
        else if (ibus_stalled)
          ram_read_addr <= ibus_stall_pc;
        else if (iBus_cmd_valid)
          ram_read_addr <= iBus_cmd_payload_pc[15:2];
     end
     ram_read <= ram[ram_read_addr];
   end
```
This uses DFFs, and exhausts the LUTs on an ice40 hx8k (mem_size is 12):

```
   reg [31:0] ram[0:(mem_size*256)-1];
   reg [31:0] ram_read;

   always @(posedge clk)
     if (prog_mode) begin
        ram_read <= ram[prog_addr >> 1];
     end else if (!rst_out) begin
        if (dBus_cmd_valid && !dBus_cmd_payload_wr && dbus_ram_access)
          ram_read <= ram[dBus_cmd_payload_address[15:2]];
        else if (ibus_stalled)
          ram_read <= ram[ibus_stall_pc];
        else if (iBus_cmd_valid)
          ram_read <= ram[iBus_cmd_payload_pc[15:2]];
     end

```
This seems more or less logical  given that Lattice BRAM needs an output buffer to use, and it's conditionally assigned here. There are fall-through cases where the buffer isn't assigned to ram_read at all. In the overall design those conditions shouldn't actualy occur, but yosys can't  infer that, as far as i can tell. 

But how about this case, where there is no way to leave the nested if statements without having assigned a value to ram_read?

 ```
 reg [31:0] ram[0:(mem_size*256)-1];
  reg [31:0] ram_read;

 always @(posedge clk)
     if (prog_mode) begin
        ram_read <= ram[prog_addr >> 1];
     end else if (!rst_out) begin
        if (dBus_cmd_valid && !dBus_cmd_payload_wr && dbus_ram_access)
          ram_read <= ram[dBus_cmd_payload_address[15:2]];
        else if (ibus_stalled)
          ram_read <= ram[ibus_stall_pc];
        else if (iBus_cmd_valid)
          ram_read <= ram[iBus_cmd_payload_pc[15:2]];
        else
          ram_read <= ram[0];
     end else
       ram_read <= ram[0];
```
Yosys doesn't seem to be able to infer that there is no pssible outcome of the if statements that leaves ram_read (the output buffer) unassigned. 

Is this intended/expected behaviour? 0.17 actually used BRAM for the first example, too.

### Expected Behavior

Yosys synthesizes the ram using BRAM blocks.

### Actual Behavior

Yosys synthesizes the ram using DFFs.

